START RECIPE
Stuffed Artichokes 
By Rachael Ray  •  December 20, 2017 

Stuffed Artichokes 
Serves 6 
This recipe originally appeared on the Rachael Ray Show. For more recipes and videos from the show visit RachaelRayShow.com. 

Ingredients 
3 medium-large artichokes, stems and tips of leaves trimmed 
1 lemon, halved 
About 1/2 cup EVOO – Extra Virgin Olive Oil 
4 tablespoons butter, cut into pieces 
12 anchovy fillets 
8 to 10 garlic cloves, chopped 
2 teaspoons red pepper flakes 
1 teaspoon black pepper 
About 4 cups breadcrumbs 
1 cup each grated Pecorino and Parmigiano-Reggiano cheese 
1 cup packed parsley and mint leaves, finely chopped 
Preparation 
Fill a pot large enough to fit the artichokes with water. Rub the trimmed artichokes with lemon halves then squeeze lemons into the water. Add artichokes and bring to a boil. 

Cook the artichokes until leaves are tender and you can just peel one away from base. Cold-shock the artichokes and drain upside down. Remove the center leaves and use a grapefruit spoon or a soup spoon to scrape out the choke from center. 

Heat a large skillet over medium heat with EVOO. Melt butter into oil and add anchovies, breaking them up until they melt away. Add garlic and red and black pepper, stir a minute or so, then add breadcrumbs. Let them absorb the oil and butter then toast until deep golden and fragrant. Cool. 

Preheat oven to 425°F. 

Combine cheese and parsley and mint and mix in cooled breadcrumbs. 

Add 1/8-inch chicken stock or water to a casserole dish. Fill the artichokes with the breadcrumb mixture, stuffing between each leaf and filling the center. Place artichokes in the casserole dish and bake to heat through and until edges of leaves curl in and brown, about 20 minutes. 

START RECIPE
Salty Butterscotch Dark Hot Chocolate 
By Andrew Kaplan  •  December 19, 2017 

Salty Butterscotch Dark Hot Chocolate 
Makes 2 cups 
Ingredients 
1 cup heavy cream, optional 
Pinch powdered sugar, optional 
4 oz. dark chocolate (plus a little more for garnish, optional) 
2 teaspoons butterscotch sauce/topping, plus more for garnish 
2 cups milk 
1/4 – 1/2 teaspoon salt 
Flaky salt, garnish, optional 
Preparation 
Place heavy cream in a stand mixer and whip on high speed. Add a few pinches of powdered sugar and whip until medium or stiff peaks form. If you do not have a stand mixer, you may use a handheld mixer – or if using a whisk, beat by hand. When finished, place in fridge until ready to use. 

Place a small nonstick saucepot or skillet over low heat and add the dark chocolate and butterscotch. Gently stir with a whisk until melted and then slowly add the milk. Whisk until smooth and incorporated and heated through- no need to boil. When steaming, add 1/4 teaspoon of salt and stir to dissolve. Taste the hot chocolate and if you want a little more salt, add the remaining 1/4 teaspoon and stir. 

Divide between 2 mugs, place a dollop of whipped cream on top and garnish with a drizzle of butterscotch sauce and/or a light dusting of flaky salt. 

