Pumpkin Oatmeal Breakfast Bars Recipe 
Jamie Larrison (Contributing Writer) 

This post may contain affiliate links which won’t change your price but will share some commission. 

31 
Pumpkin Oatmeal Breakfast Bar Recipe (Whole Grain, Low Sugar) - this delicious breakfast bar is a great grab and go breakfast option for busy weeks!This post is from KS contributor Jamie Larrison of How To Just About Anything. 

Let me describe your typical morning… 
You wake up all on your own, completely refreshed and have ample time to shower, get dressed and do your hair. You’re greeted at the breakfast table by a row of smiling, patient faces. You fry some eggs and bacon as you dexterously dip and cook the French toast, all while the coffee steams in the background. Your toddler of course doesn’t bother this process at all, and most certainly doesn’t grab the egg carton off the counter and smash it onto the floor. 

Kudos to you if your morning actually looks like this! But more often that not mornings can be a rushed, chaotic mess. And trying to fit a nutritious breakfast, that even your pickiest child will love, in the mix can seem impossible. 

Hurried Mornings 
Mornings can be rushed for a variety of reasons. Maybe everyone was up too late the night before and caught some extra zzz’s. Or maybe the dog decided to use your clean, but not folded yet, laundry pile instead of the outdoors to do his business. And just maybe that laundry pile had all the school uniforms in it. 

Even if you homeschool, you don’t want to spend all day on your morning routine. Even if your kids aren’t in school yet, or you don’t have kids, you still don’t want to waste tons of time in the mornings. 


I remember certain college mornings where I would literally roll out of bed, put on my shoes, grab a Slim Fast and head to class. I think it can safely be said that we all want to streamline things. And hopefully no one reading this resorts to Slim Fast for breakfast! Please don’t drink Slim Fast. 

I Need More Options! 
Does this mean that it’s cold cereal for breakfast every morning? This breakfast solution can get old quickly . Especially if you’re trying to go gluten free. A person can only eat so many bowls of rice chex. Or maybe you’ve opted for the healthier route and get the organic box that was ONLY $4.95 on sale. Those add up fast! 

I usually have time to make a simple, yet nutritious, breakfast. Like a quick batch of gluten free pumpkin pancakes. Or some green eggs and ham that have a secret nutritious ingredient my toddler loves. 

But other mornings I just don’t have the time! Sometimes I’m just worn out from making breakfast and need a break. These pumpkin oatmeal breakfast bars are the solution to multiple breakfast issues. 

What’s so Great About These Oatmeal Breakfast Bars? 
They’re soft and chewy so they’re suitable for an older baby. They’re slightly sweet and packed with a pumpkin flavor that will appeal to picky eaters. You can also make these the night before and literally just grab one as you head out the door. I’ve even stowed one of these away in a reusable container for an easy way to nourish a hungry little one. Perfect for when the trip to the grocery store is taking longer than expected. 

Pumpkin Oatmeal Breakfast Bar Recipe (Whole Grain, Low Sugar) - this delicious breakfast bar is a great grab and go breakfast option for busy weeks!These are naturally gluten and dairy free, so they’re safe for those with these allergies. Even if you don’t make it a point to avoid those foods, these bars are delicious to have on hand. They have a soft, cakelike texture to them. 

I also love the autumn flavor to this. To me, a good pumpkin baked good full of cinnamon and ginger is the perfect breakfast (or snack) to munch on. Especially when it’s paired with a foamy homemade vanilla latte or a diy creamy pumpkin frappe. 

Breakfast Book 200Looking for more quick, easy, gluten-free options? 
Need ideas to stay away from the cold cereal aisle at the store? 

Find many more recipes (including an allergen-free index!) in Katie’s eBook The Healthy Breakfast Book. 



Not only is pumpkin a popular seasonal favorite, but it’s super good for you too! One serving of these oatmeal bars will give you 40% of the vitamin A needed for the day. It has 94 mg of potassium and is high in several other key nutrients, like vitamin C. 
So enough about how awesome these are. Go make some! 

